data.title: ManpowerGroup Inc. SEC 10-Q Report
data.description:
ManpowerGroup Inc., a global leader in workforce solutions, has released its Form 10-Q report for the third quarter of 2025. The report provides a comprehensive overview of the company's financial performance and operational highlights, reflecting the company's strategic initiatives and market conditions.

Financial Highlights

  • Revenues from services: $4,634.4 million, increased by 2.3% compared to the third quarter of 2024, primarily driven by a revenue increase in the Americas and Southern Europe, offset by decreases in Northern Europe and APME.
  • Gross profit: $768.9 million, decreased by 1.7% compared to the third quarter of 2024, with a gross profit margin of 16.6%, down 70 basis points due to business mix changes and lower permanent recruitment activity.
  • Operating profit: $66.6 million, decreased by 6.1% compared to the third quarter of 2024, with an operating profit margin of 1.4%, down 20 basis points due to decreased gross profit margin and non-recurrence of prior year cost reductions.
  • Net earnings: $18.0 million, decreased by 20.9% compared to the third quarter of 2024, impacted by restructuring costs and a non-cash currency translation charge related to the Argentina business.
  • Net earnings per share – diluted: $0.38, decreased by 18.8% compared to the third quarter of 2024, with a decrease in weighted average shares due to share repurchases.

Business Highlights

  • Revenue Segments: The Americas segment saw a 4.6% increase in revenue, driven by higher demand for Manpower staffing services, despite a decrease in Experis interim services. Southern Europe experienced a 5.2% increase, primarily due to favorable currency exchange rates, while Northern Europe saw a 1.4% decrease due to reduced demand in staffing and interim services. APME's revenue decreased by 7.5%, largely due to the disposition of the Korea business.
  • Geographical Performance: In the Americas, the United States experienced a slight revenue decrease of 0.9%, offset by growth in other countries. Southern Europe, particularly Italy, showed strong growth with a 10.3% increase in revenue, driven by demand for staffing services. Northern Europe faced challenges with significant revenue decreases in the UK and Germany, while Belgium showed positive growth. APME's performance was impacted by the Korea business disposition, but Japan and India showed revenue increases.
  • Sales Units: There was a notable increase in demand for Manpower staffing services across several regions, contributing to the overall revenue growth in those segments.
  • Future Outlook: The company anticipates a mixed business environment due to ongoing macroeconomic and geopolitical uncertainties. While some regions show signs of stabilization, many employers remain cautious, awaiting greater economic clarity before increasing workforce investments. The company expects continued resilience in Latin America and Asia Pacific, with cautious optimism in parts of Europe and North America.

SEC Filing: ManpowerGroup Inc. [ MAN ] - 10-Q - Oct. 31, 2025

data.title: Ingersoll Rand Inc. SEC 10-Q Report
data.description:
Ingersoll Rand Inc., a global leader in industrial technologies and services, has released its Form 10-Q report for the third quarter of 2025. The report highlights the company's robust financial performance and strategic business advancements, driven by successful acquisitions and operational efficiencies.

Financial Highlights

Ingersoll Rand Inc. reported strong financial results for the three months ended September 30, 2025, showcasing significant growth across key metrics:

  • Revenues: $1,955.0 million, reflecting an increase from $1,861.0 million in the same period of 2024.
  • Gross Profit: $855.2 million, up from $815.0 million in the same period of 2024, indicating improved cost management.
  • Operating Income: $375.5 million, compared to $356.3 million in the same period of 2024, showing enhanced operational efficiency.
  • Net Income: $245.8 million, an increase from $223.4 million in the same period of 2024, driven by higher revenues and controlled expenses.
  • Net Income Attributable to Ingersoll Rand Inc.: $244.1 million, compared to $221.6 million in the same period of 2024.
  • Basic Earnings Per Share: $0.62, up from $0.55 in the same period of 2024.
  • Diluted Earnings Per Share: $0.61, compared to $0.54 in the same period of 2024.

Business Highlights

Ingersoll Rand Inc. also reported notable business achievements and strategic initiatives during the third quarter of 2025:

  • Revenue Segments: The Industrial Technologies and Services segment saw significant contributions from acquisitions, including SSI Aeration, Excelsior Blower Systems, and TMIC/Adicomp, enhancing the segment's offerings in compressors, blowers, and pumps.
  • Revenue Segments: The Precision and Science Technologies segment benefited from acquisitions such as Lead Fluid and Dave Barry Plastics, which expanded the company's capabilities in fluid-handling products and plastic solutions for life sciences.
  • Geographical Performance: The company experienced strong performance in its European operations, supported by strategic acquisitions and favorable foreign currency translation adjustments.
  • Sales Units: The acquisitions completed in 2025 contributed $101.6 million in revenue and $12.6 million in operating income for the nine-month period, indicating successful integration and operational performance.
  • New Product Launches: The acquisition of SSI Aeration allows the company to offer comprehensive wastewater treatment solutions by combining low-pressure compressors with SSI's aeration technology.
  • New Production Launches: The acquisition of TMIC/Adicomp enhances the company's production capabilities in air and gas compressors, particularly in the renewable natural gas industry.
  • Future Outlook: Management anticipates continued growth through strategic acquisitions and integration, focusing on expanding market share in high-growth, sustainable end markets.

SEC Filing: Ingersoll Rand Inc. [ IR ] - 10-Q - Oct. 31, 2025

data.title: DigitalBridge Group, Inc. SEC 10-Q Report
data.description:
DigitalBridge Group, Inc., a leading global investment firm focused on digital infrastructure, has released its Form 10-Q report for the third quarter. The report provides a comprehensive overview of the company's financial performance and business operations, reflecting both challenges and strategic initiatives in the digital infrastructure sector.

Financial Highlights

DigitalBridge Group, Inc. reported the following key financial metrics for the third quarter:

  • Total Revenues: $3.8 million, reflecting a significant decrease from the previous year due to a reversal in carried interest allocation.
  • Net Income (Loss): $(12.8) million, compared to a net income of $48.3 million in the prior year, primarily driven by a reversal in carried interest allocation.
  • Net Income (Loss) Attributable to Common Stockholders: $16.8 million, showing a recovery from a loss in the previous year.
  • Net Income (Loss) Per Share—Basic: $0.09, indicating a positive turnaround from a loss per share in the previous year.
  • Net Income (Loss) Per Share—Diluted: $0.09, consistent with the basic earnings per share, reflecting the company's improved financial performance.

Business Highlights

The company's business performance for the third quarter includes the following highlights:

  • Revenue Segments: The company reported fee revenue primarily from management fees, incentive fees, and other fees. Management fees are derived from commingled equity funds, credit and other equity funds, co-investment vehicles, and liquid strategy funds. Incentive fees are earned from sub-advisory accounts in the liquid securities strategy.
  • Future Outlook: The company is focused on expanding its digital infrastructure investment management platform, with an emphasis on value-add digital infrastructure equity offerings and other investment strategies. The management anticipates continued growth in digital infrastructure investments, driven by increasing demand for data centers, cell towers, and fiber networks.

SEC Filing: DigitalBridge Group, Inc. [ DBRG ] - 10-Q - Oct. 31, 2025

data.title: DIGITAL REALTY TRUST, INC. SEC 10-Q Report
data.description:
Digital Realty Trust, Inc., a leading global provider of data center, colocation, and interconnection solutions, has released its Form 10-Q report for the third quarter of 2025. The report highlights significant financial and operational achievements, reflecting the company's robust performance and strategic initiatives in the data center industry.

Financial Highlights

Total Operating Revenues: $1,577 million, an increase of approximately $146 million or 10.2% compared to the same period in 2024. This growth was driven by new leasing and renewals across all regions and the strengthening of foreign exchange rates.

Net Income Available to Common Stockholders: $58 million, up from $41 million in the same period in 2024. This increase reflects improved operational performance and gains from property dispositions.

Diluted FFO per share and unit: $1.65, up from $1.55 in the same period in 2024, indicating strong funds from operations performance.

Total Operating Expenses: $1,439 million, an increase of $176 million or 13.9% compared to the same period in 2024. This rise was primarily due to higher property level operating expenses and increased general and administrative costs.

Depreciation and Amortization: $497 million, an increase of $37 million or 8.0% compared to the same period in 2024, reflecting continued investment in property and infrastructure.

Business Highlights

Revenue Segments: The company's revenue is primarily generated from rental income from data centers. The revenue is segmented into stabilized and non-stabilized portfolios, with significant contributions from new leasing and renewals across all regions.

Geographical Performance: North America remains the largest region with 92 data center buildings and a net rentable square footage of 18,598, maintaining an occupancy rate of 85.5%. Europe follows with 107 buildings and a net rentable square footage of 9,332, with an occupancy rate of 78.4%. The Asia Pacific region shows growth with an occupancy rate increase to 82.7%.

Sales Units: The company reported leasing activity with renewals and new leases signed, totaling 2,046 rentable square feet for 0-1 MW and 1,431 rentable square feet for >1 MW categories.

New Production Launches: The company formed a joint venture with Bersama Digital Infrastructure Asia to develop and operate data centers in Indonesia, acquiring a 50% interest in the joint venture, which includes two land parcels and two buildings in Jakarta.

Future Outlook: The company anticipates continued internal growth through the development of existing space, acquisition of land for future development, and acquisition of new properties. It aims to achieve superior risk-adjusted returns and drive revenue growth and operating efficiencies.

Operational Strategy: Digital Realty Trust, Inc. focuses on maximizing sustainable long-term growth in earnings and funds from operations per share and unit, cash flow, and returns to stockholders. The strategy includes diversifying product offerings, accelerating global reach, and managing and leasing assets aggressively to increase cash flow.

Leasing Activities: The company continues to see strong demand in key metropolitan areas for data center space, expecting average aggregate rental rates on renewed data center leases for 2025 expirations to be positive compared to current rates.

Occupancy Rates: The consolidated portfolio occupancy rate is 83.1%, with the managed unconsolidated portfolio showing a high occupancy rate of 93.5%.

Development Projects: The company has significant investments in development projects, with a focus on future development capacity and data center construction, reflecting a commitment to expanding its operational footprint.

SEC Filing: DIGITAL REALTY TRUST, INC. [ DLR ] - 10-Q - Oct. 31, 2025

data.title: DANA Inc SEC 10-Q Report
data.description:
DANA Inc, a global leader in the design and manufacture of highly engineered driveline, sealing, and thermal-management technologies, has released its Form 10-Q report for the third quarter of 2025. The report highlights the company's financial performance and key business activities, reflecting its strategic initiatives and market dynamics.

Financial Highlights

  • Net Sales: $1,917 million for the three months ended September 30, 2025, compared to $1,897 million for the same period in 2024, reflecting a slight increase in sales.
  • Earnings (loss) from continuing operations before interest and income taxes: $53 million for the three months ended September 30, 2025, compared to a loss of $8 million for the same period in 2024, indicating improved operational performance.
  • Net Income: $87 million for the three months ended September 30, 2025, compared to $11 million for the same period in 2024, driven by higher income from discontinued operations.
  • Net Income Per Share: Basic earnings per share of $0.65 for the three months ended September 30, 2025, compared to $0.03 for the same period in 2024, reflecting significant improvement in profitability.
  • Diluted EPS: $0.64 for the three months ended September 30, 2025, compared to $0.03 for the same period in 2024, highlighting enhanced earnings performance.

Business Highlights

  • Segment Realignment: Dana Incorporated has realigned its operating segments to streamline business operations and enhance market approach. The former Power Technologies segment has been integrated into the Light Vehicle and Commercial Vehicle segments, focusing on OEM-facing and aftermarket businesses respectively.
  • Divestiture of Off-Highway Business: Dana has entered into an agreement to sell its Off-Highway business to Allison Transmission Holdings, Inc. This strategic move is aimed at focusing on core on-highway markets, with the transaction expected to close in the fourth quarter of 2025.
  • Geographical Performance: The Light Vehicle segment saw varied performance across regions, with North America and Europe showing stable production, while South America and Asia Pacific experienced fluctuations. The Commercial Vehicle segment faced a decrease in North American production but saw growth in South America.
  • Sales Units and Production Volumes: The Light Vehicle segment reported external sales of $1,353 million for the third quarter of 2025, while the Commercial Vehicle segment reported $564 million. These figures reflect the company's focus on enhancing operational efficiency and market presence.
  • Future Outlook: Dana projects sales of approximately $7,400 million for 2025, with an adjusted EBITDA of around $590 million. The company plans to use proceeds from the Off-Highway business sale to strengthen its financial position and return capital to shareholders.
  • Commodity Costs Impact: The company experienced a decrease in earnings due to higher commodity prices, although material cost recovery pricing actions helped offset some of these impacts.
  • Foreign Currency Impact: International currency movements, particularly the weakening of the Brazilian real, Indian rupee, and Mexican peso, impacted sales, although this was partially offset by a stronger euro and other currencies.

SEC Filing: DANA Inc [ DAN ] - 10-Q - Oct. 31, 2025

data.title: Astrotech Names Bartley Interim Finance Chief After Cañas's Resignation
data.description:
By Katherine Hamilton

Astrotech named an interim chief financial officer after its finance chief announced her resignation.

Scott Bartley, a financial consultant from outside the company, was appointed interim CFO, effective Oct. 20, the Austin, Texas, technology company said Friday.

Bartley, 56, has served as a financial consultant at Bridgepoint Consulting since 2018, and previously owned and managed Tolarus Partners.

Bartley succeeds Jennifer Cañas, whose resignation was announced on Oct. 23. Cañas was appointed chief financial officer in May after serving as controller since 2022.

Write to Katherine Hamilton at katherine.hamilton@wsj.com

data.title: Mobile-health Network Solutions Reports FY2025 Results and Operational Update
data.description:
Singapore, Singapore--(Newsfile Corp. - October 31, 2025) - Mobile-health Network Solutions ("MNDR" or the "Company"), a leading AI HealthTech platform, today announced its financial results for the fiscal year ended June 30, 2025 ("FY2025"), and outlined its strategy to scale its proprietary AI-driven virtual-care platform across high-growth emerging markets.

During FY2025, the Company completed its transition from an asset-heavy structure to an asset-light virtual-care platform, significantly reducing operational costs and positioning MNDR for sustainable, scalable growth.

Management Commentary and Strategic Outlook – Efficiency for Public Good

"FY2025 marked a defining year as MNDR completed its transformation into an AI-powered, asset-light health platform," said Dr. Siaw Tung Yeng, Co-CEO of MNDR. "In an era where healthcare systems face rising costs and stretched resources, our mission is to stay lean, stay intelligent, and stay aligned with public health priorities. In the coming year, MNDR will strengthen partnerships with healthcare networks, corporate health programs, and public agencies in order to embed our Health Operating System where it can deliver the most impact."

Dr. Rachel Teoh, Co-CEO of MNDR, added, "Our strategy is not about scaling for its own sake, but scaling intelligently using data, automation, and empathy to deliver better outcomes at lower cost. In this future, AI doctors won't be confined to apps — intelligent robots and drones will roll and fly into the field during crises, delivering medicine to remote regions and maintaining care continuity when infrastructure fails. That's the future MNDR is building — a world where help always arrives."

FY2025 Financial and Strategic Highlights

Results for the year reflect short-term effects of MNDR's structural transformation, alongside ongoing execution of key international initiatives:

  • Financial Discipline: Net loss narrowed to US$3.4 million from US$15.6 million in FY2024, driven by cost optimization and lower structural overhead.

  • Revenue: FY2025 revenue was US$7.7 million, a 45.3% year-on-year decline, reflecting the strategic exit from legacy clinic operations towards a scalable virtual-care platform.

  • Improved Operational Focus: The Company's streamlined operating structure reduced complexity and regulatory exposure associated with physical healthcare facilities, enabling management to concentrate resources on technology innovation and regional stability.

Proprietary Large Language Model, Phi GPT:

  • Phi GPT, launched by the Company in September 2025, forms the foundation of a new generation of clinical-support tools — including AI Checker and AI Notes — that employ retrieval augmented generation (RAG) and are fine-tuned on doctor-validated medical corpora. These tools use structured clinical data to deliver context-aware documentation and workflow automation, enhancing accuracy and efficiency across provider networks.

  • Powered by Phi GPT, MNDR launched Aiko, a multilingual, context-aware health intelligence patient companion embedded in the Company's Health Operating System (HOS). Using structured patient data and validated clinical knowledge, Aiko delivers adaptive, privacy-secure recommendations that help patients manage medications, prevention, and chronic care.

Ecosystem and Network Expansion:

  • In Indonesia, MNDR expanded its doctor network through professional webinars and engagement programs that enhance clinical collaboration and digital readiness, reinforcing the Company's mission to build a connected community of care within its HOS.

  • Extending its model beyond Asia, MNDR formed a strategic partnership with a Ghana-based healthcare provider to deliver virtual care and AI-powered health services to underserved communities in Africa—the Company's first entry into the region's fast-growing digital health market.

  • MNDR maintains a disciplined capital strategy, utilizing its US$300 million At-the-Market (ATM) facility and US$10 million SEPA commitment to support growth initiatives and ensure balance sheet flexibility.

About Mobile-health Network Solutions

Mobile-health Network Solutions is a leading AI-powered digital health platform headquartered in Singapore, with operations across Southeast Asia and expanding into the US. The company provides telemedicine, AI-driven health tools, and virtual clinic infrastructure to empower patients and doctors worldwide. Its mission is to make healthcare accessible, intelligent, and human - through technology. For more information, please visit our website.

data.title: Bitcoin breaks October streak with first monthly loss since 2018
data.description:
Key points:
  • Bitcoin set for nearly 5% decline in October
  • Largest crypto liquidation in history after Trump's tariff announcement
  • Bitcoin still up over 16% this year despite October decline

By Hannah Lang

Bitcoin on Friday was on track for a monthly loss in October for the first time since 2018, snapping a seven-year streak of gains that had earned the month a lucky reputation among cryptocurrency traders.

Bitcoin, the world's largest cryptocurrency, is set for a nearly 5% decline this month, as the digital asset has struggled in recent weeks amid broader market jitters and muted investor risk appetite.

Cryptocurrencies "came into October, tracking gold, tracking stocks near all-time highs, and then as uncertainty hit people for the first time maybe this year, they didn't rotate back into bitcoin en masse," said Adam McCarthy, a senior research analyst at digital market data provider Kaiko.

October saw the largest crypto liquidation in history after U.S. President Donald Trump announced a 100% tariff on Chinese imports and threatened export controls on critical software.

Bitcoin fell as low as $104,782.88 during the October 10-11 period, after setting a fresh record high just days earlier above $126,000.

"That washout on the 10th, it really reminded people that this asset class is very narrow," said McCarthy. "It's bitcoin and (ether), and even those can still have 10% drawdowns in 15, 20 minutes."

A whirlwind October is set to end with spooked investors unsure of the global monetary policy path in the near term, as the U.S. Federal Reserve pushed back against market bets that it would continue to cut rates this year as the government shutdown blocks crucial economic data.

Meanwhile, several influential figures have expressed concerns about high valuations in equity markets. JPMorgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon earlier this month warned of a heightened risk of a significant correction in the U.S. stock market within the next six months to two years.

"Participants remain hesitant as they process what has become the largest liquidation event on record. This caution persists amid ongoing speculation about specific vulnerabilities that may still exist in the system," said Jake Ostrovskis, head of trading firm Wintermute's over-the-counter desk.

Despite its October decline, bitcoin is still up more than 16% so far this year.

Cryptocurrencies have generally enjoyed a boost this year as Trump has embraced digital assets, which has led to the dismissal of a spate of lawsuits against prominent crypto platforms and a shift by Trump's financial regulators to create specialized rules to accommodate digital assets.

data.title: EVEREST GROUP, LTD. SEC 10-Q Report
data.description:
EVEREST GROUP, LTD., a global leader in reinsurance and insurance, has released its Form 10-Q report for the third quarter of the fiscal year. The report provides a comprehensive overview of the company's financial and operational performance, highlighting key metrics and business activities that have shaped the quarter. The company continues to navigate a complex market environment, driven by its strategic initiatives and robust risk management practices.

Financial Highlights

  • Total Revenues: $13,073 million, reflecting a year-over-year increase driven by higher premiums earned and net investment income.
  • Net Income (Loss): $1,145 million, a decrease compared to the previous year, impacted by higher incurred losses and loss adjustment expenses.
  • Diluted EPS: $27.06, indicating a decline from the prior year, primarily due to increased claims and expenses.
  • Net Investment Income: $1,563 million, showing growth from the previous year, supported by higher returns from fixed maturities and limited partnerships.

Business Highlights

  • Segment Performance: The company operates through two main segments: Reinsurance and Insurance. The Reinsurance segment writes worldwide property and casualty reinsurance and specialty lines of business, while the Insurance segment writes property and casualty insurance directly and through brokers. Both segments are managed independently but adhere to corporate guidelines regarding pricing, risk management, and capital allocation.
  • Geographical Performance: The Reinsurance business is conducted through offices in the U.S., Bermuda, Ireland, Canada, Singapore, the U.K., and Switzerland. The Insurance business operates in the U.S., Bermuda, Canada, Europe, Singapore, and South America, with branches in Australia, the U.K., the Netherlands, France, Germany, Italy, and Spain. This broad geographical presence allows the company to diversify its risk and capitalize on regional market opportunities.
  • Operational Challenges: The company faced challenges related to the strengthening of U.S. casualty reserves and aviation losses associated with the Russia/Ukraine war, which impacted the reserve for losses and loss adjustment expenses. The net unfavorable development on prior year reserves was primarily due to these factors.
  • Future Outlook: The company continues to evaluate its segments as the business evolves and may further refine its segments and financial performance measures. The management is focused on maintaining strong underwriting results and managing aggregate catastrophe exposures effectively.
  • New Segment Introduction: During the fourth quarter of 2024, the company introduced a new segment called 'Other', which includes run-off business and certain discontinued insurance programs. This segment does not actively sell products but manages existing policies and settlements.

data.title: CASELLA WASTE SYSTEMS INC SEC 10-Q Report
data.description:
Casella Waste Systems Inc., a leading provider of integrated solid waste services, has released its Form 10-Q report for the third quarter of 2025. The report highlights significant growth in both financial and operational metrics, underscoring the company's robust performance across all segments and regions.

Financial Highlights

  • Total Revenues: $485.351 million, reflecting a significant increase from $411.627 million in the same period last year, driven by growth across all segments.
  • Operating Income: $29.369 million, up from $24.379 million in the prior year, indicating improved operational efficiency.
  • Net Income: $9.984 million, compared to $5.771 million in the previous year, showcasing enhanced profitability.
  • Basic Earnings Per Share (EPS): $0.16, an increase from $0.10, reflecting higher net income attributable to common stockholders.
  • Diluted EPS: $0.16, up from $0.10, consistent with the increase in net income and reflecting the impact of potential dilutive securities.

Business Highlights

  • Revenue Segments: The company operates through four main segments: Eastern, Western, Mid-Atlantic, and Resource Solutions. The Eastern segment generated $125.975 million, the Western segment $175.124 million, the Mid-Atlantic segment $91.071 million, and Resource Solutions $93.181 million in third-party revenues for the three months ended September 30, 2025.
  • Geographical Performance: The Eastern region saw a significant increase in revenues, driven by strong performance in collection services. The Western region also experienced growth, particularly in landfill and transfer station services. The Mid-Atlantic region faced challenges, resulting in a slight decrease in operating income.
  • Sales Units: The company reported strong collection service performance, with significant contributions from the Eastern and Western regions. The Resource Solutions segment also showed robust activity, particularly in processing and National Accounts services.
  • Future Outlook: Management anticipates continued growth in the Resource Solutions segment, leveraging core competencies in materials processing and industrial recycling. The company is focused on integrating recent acquisitions to enhance operational efficiency and expand service offerings.
  • Operational Strategy: The company is committed to expanding its integrated solid waste services across its operating regions, with a focus on enhancing its Resource Solutions offerings to meet diverse customer needs.

data.title: AT&T INC. SEC 10-Q Report
data.description:
AT&T Inc., a leading telecommunications and media company, has released its latest Form 10-Q report, highlighting significant improvements in both financial and operational performance. The report covers the third quarter of 2025 and provides insights into the company's revenue growth, profitability, and strategic business initiatives.

Financial Highlights

  • Total Operating Revenues: $30,709 million, increased by 1.6% from the previous year, driven by higher Mobility and Consumer Wireline revenues.
  • Operating Income: $6,119 million, significantly increased from $2,116 million in the previous year, reflecting improved operational efficiency and cost management.
  • Net Income: $9,677 million, a substantial increase from $145 million in the previous year, primarily due to a gain on the sale of the interest in DIRECTV.
  • Net Income (Loss) Attributable to Common Stock: $9,278 million, compared to a loss of $226 million in the previous year, highlighting a strong recovery in profitability.
  • Basic Earnings (Loss) Per Share Attributable to Common Stock: $1.29, compared to a loss of $0.03 per share in the previous year, indicating improved earnings performance.
  • Diluted Earnings (Loss) Per Share Attributable to Common Stock: $1.29, compared to a loss of $0.03 per share in the previous year, reflecting enhanced shareholder value.

Business Highlights

  • Revenue Segments: The Communications segment saw a 1.5% increase in operating revenues for the third quarter of 2025, driven by growth in Mobility and Consumer Wireline, despite a decline in Business Wireline. Mobility revenues increased by 3.1% due to higher service and equipment sales, while Consumer Wireline grew by 4.1%. Business Wireline experienced a 7.8% decline, reflecting reduced demand for legacy services.
  • Geographical Performance: In the Latin America segment, revenues were higher in the third quarter but lower for the first nine months of 2025 due to unfavorable foreign exchange impacts earlier in the year.
  • Sales Units: Mobility reported a 2.5% increase in total subscribers, reaching 118.982 million, with postpaid subscribers growing by 2.1% to 90.255 million. Prepaid subscribers decreased by 3.4%, while reseller subscribers increased by 20.1%.
  • Mobility Net Additions: The third quarter saw 748,000 net subscriber additions in Mobility, a 21.2% increase from the previous year, driven by strong reseller growth and postpaid phone net additions.
  • Churn Rates: Postpaid churn increased to 1.07% in the third quarter, up from 0.93% in the previous year, influenced by a larger customer base reaching the end of device financing periods.
  • Future Outlook: The company anticipates lower depreciation expenses in the fourth quarter of 2025 compared to the prior year, as certain legacy assets become fully depreciated. Full-year depreciation is expected to remain consistent with the previous year.
